Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1937, the Appalachian Trail was officially completed with over 2,200 miles of hiking trails across 14 states.
¬†
The trail was first proposed in 1921 to create a trail that connected farms and wilderness work camps throughout the Appalachian Mountains from the highest point in the North to the highest point in the South to encourage Americans to explore their country through hiking. 

Today, the trail begins at Springer Mountain in Georgia and ends at Mt. Katahdin in Maine. Approximately three million people hike a portion of the trail each year, with only over 20,000 completing the entire route. ¬†
¬†
Notable hikers include WWII veteran and trailblazer Earl Shaffer, who became the first person to hike the entire trail in 1948 as a way to ‚Äúwalk the war out of [his] system‚Äù, and Emma Gatewood, a 67-year-old grandmother who completed the trail in five months.

Name: Clyburn, James E.
text:
On this day in 1935, President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed the Social Security Act into law.

It marked the first time the U.S. government established a national system to ensure older Americans could retire with dignity.

Today, Social Security is projected to face a funding shortfall by the early to mid-2030s.

Trump and MAGA Republicans have made this worse with their ‚ÄúBig Ugly Bill,‚Äù which is estimated to reduce Social Security‚Äôs revenue by about $30 billion per year.

We can strengthen Social Security by subjecting high income to payroll taxes.

Right now, a billionaire pays the same amount into Social Security as someone making about $168,600 a year ‚Äî the current cap on taxable wages. That‚Äôs not right.

It‚Äôs time for the wealthiest Americans to pay their fair share so that every American can retire with the benefits they've spent a lifetime earning.

üöí Clay County Fire Station 20 is now in service!

This station is located at 1305 Idlewild Avenue in Green Cove Springs.

Station 20 is a state-of-the-art facility designed to meet the needs of our growing community‚Äîwith advanced safety features and increased space for more firefighters, equipment, and vehicles.

This station also has Clay County's first 9/11 Memorial. In front of the station, you will see the display of two beams of exterior wall structural steel, reported to have been from the 68th floor of World Trade Center 1, the North Tower. Additionally, a sapling from a Callery pear tree that once stood at the original World Trade Center, now known as the Survivor Tree, will also be planted at the Memorial.

Name: Thanedar, Shri
text:
From opening new investment opportunities to protecting our supply chain from Trump‚Äôs attacks, cryptocurrency can benefit everyone.

Credit card payments cost businesses up to 3.5% in fees, which is then passed on to the consumer. Money orders are a popular way to send money, but can be expensive and hard to access. Stablecoins‚Äîdigital dollars powered by blockchain‚Äîlet people send money instantly for pennies, eliminating a hidden tax we all pay.

As a former small business owner, I know how difficult it is to build a small business. Traditional credit card or check payments can take up to 7 days to clear, further exacerbating these difficulties. With blockchain, payments settle in seconds, giving businesses immediate access to funds they can use to grow their business and a greater ability to compete globally‚Äîcritical when 74% of economic activity is outside the U.S.

I‚Äôm encouraged by bipartisan bills like the GENIUS and CLARITY Acts, which create a clear, bipartisan, pro-innovation regulatory framework for digital assets. Inconsistent state regulations have driven 1 in 3 blockchain innovators overseas‚Äîhurting our economy and competitiveness. #CryptoDayOfAction

I've been saying the St. Louis Processing and Delivery Center was a black hole and mail went there to die, but it turns out that was an understatement.¬†

Following repeated calls for an investigation into the mail issues there from me and my colleagues in Missouri and Illinois, the USPS Office of Inspector General released their findings from the audit they conducted over the last 3 months at the St. Louis facility.
¬†
In just two days in June, almost 2.6 million pieces of mail were delayed. If that wasn‚Äôt bad enough, they only reported around 1.5 million pieces as delayed. They weren't even reporting the missed mail correctly! On top of that, over 50% of all outbound mail trips from the STL processing facility from May 2024 - April 2025 were late or canceled. Local carriers can‚Äôt deliver the mail if it doesn‚Äôt get to them. That‚Äôs completely unacceptable.
¬†
Management acknowledges that there were issues and promised to fix them. That‚Äôs not gonna cut it. It‚Äôs time for management to go and the Postal Service needs to overhaul this facility completely so Northeast Missouri can start getting their mail on time once again.¬†

Name: Blunt Rochester, Lisa
text:
I am deeply saddened to hear of the passing of a true Delaware political giant, Mike Castle. Governor Castle was a fixture in Delaware politics for nearly half a century. As one of his hundreds of thousands of constituents, I always admired how gracefully he led. From his focus on educating our children and maintaining fiscal responsibility to his commitment to protecting our environment, his presence throughout our state will be missed.

He served the First State selflessly, with a pragmatic approach and relentless optimism. One of my fondest memories of Mike was with my late dad, Ted Blunt. Not only did they share a love of public service, but they also shared a love of basketball. They joked about playing basketball on the same team and against each other on several occasions over the years. His steady hand and attunement to the needs of his constituents made him unique ‚Äî a quality that will be missed in politically challenging times such as these. His legacy will surely live on. I send my deepest condolences to his wife, Jane, his family and loved ones, and all who crossed his path. May he rest in eternal peace.

Name: Rulli, Michael A.
text:
Today, Catholics celebrate the Assumption of the Blessed Virgin Mary, when Mary was taken into Heaven, body and soul, at the end of her life on Earth. In Italy, this August holiday has even older roots, dating back to Emperor Augustus in 18 B.C. The name Ferragosto comes from the Latin Feriae Augusti, meaning the festivals of Augustus, a time for rest and celebration.

For generations, August was when most Italians took their ferie, or vacation. Years ago, shops and offices would close on August 1, and families would spend the month at the beach, in the mountains, or in the countryside. Cities would grow quiet, and finding an open store was rare. Today, vacations may be shorter, but August 15 remains the heart of summer and a cherished national holiday.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories from across our district of individuals who dedicate their lives to strengthening our communities, uplifting others, and leaving a lasting mark on the place we call home. Today, we shine a light on a remarkable woman whose leadership and service have shaped the very backbone of our local economy. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero, Susan Harkins of Levittown.
 
Yesterday, we had the honor of celebrating Susan‚Äôs 45 years of service with the @LowerBksChamber‚Äîa milestone that reflects not only remarkable longevity, but a legacy of true and lasting impact. For nearly half a century, Susan has been a driving force behind the Chamber‚Äôs mission‚Äîchampioning our businesses, empowering professionals, and creating opportunities that have strengthened the very foundation of our community.
 
The @USChamber of Commerce is more than an organization‚Äîit is the backbone of our local economy, where businesses come together to share ideas, build connections, and grow. For 45 years, Susan Harkins has been the heart of that mission, from her early days supporting Chamber committees to her leadership today as Professional Development Specialist. As a longtime partner of our local Chambers, I know firsthand how critical this work is to creating opportunity, and I‚Äôve been proud to collaborate on initiatives that bring new investment, strengthen workforce development, and ensure small businesses have the tools to thrive. At every step, leaders like Susan make that progress possible.
 
Her work with Leadership Bucks County, now in its 29th year, has cultivated a generation of civic and business leaders who continue to shape our region. Through programs like the Keynote Morning Meeting, Business Card Exchange, and Young Professionals Summits, Susan has created the networks, the mentorship, and the opportunities that drive careers forward and strengthen our business community as a whole.

Her impact cannot be measured by job titles or events alone‚Äîit is reflected in every professional she mentored, every student she supported, every small business she helped connect, and every leader she inspired to step forward. Simply put, the progress and prosperity of Lower Bucks County would not be what it is today without Susan.
 
Beyond the Chamber, she has carried that same spirit of service into her work with the A. Marlyn Moyer, Jr. Scholarship Foundation and the Bucks County Technical High School Foundation for Education Excellence‚Äîinvesting in the success of students and ensuring opportunity for the next generation.
 
Susan has been a builder of leaders, a champion of business, and a trusted guide for thousands who have walked through the Chamber‚Äôs doors. Please join me in congratulating her on 45 years of excellence and thanking her for all she has done for our community!

Friday in the First

Colleen Nicholas of Edenton has devoted more than 30 years to special education ‚Äî teaching, mentoring, and advocating for students with disabilities. Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
I teamed up with @repkmr to introduce the bipartisan Keep Call Centers in America Act of 2025.

When call center jobs are shipped overseas, it weakens our economic security, erodes consumer protections, and strips jobs and investment from our communities. This bill puts a stop to that‚Äîprotecting American workers, holding corporations accountable, and ensuring customers get the service and transparency they deserve.

With 3 million Americans working in call centers and 150,000 jobs projected to be lost by 2033, this is about more than convenience on the phone‚Äîit‚Äôs about defending American jobs and economic strength.

Our Keep Call Centers in America Act will:

‚úÖ Require companies to disclose when they offshore jobs
‚úÖ Block offshoring firms from new federal contracts and funding
‚úÖ Guarantee federal call center work stays in the U.S.
‚úÖ Give customers the right to speak with a U.S.-based worker if they ask

Bipartisan. Pro-worker. Pro-America. That‚Äôs what this bill is about.

Clean energy tax credits are being phased out, raising energy prices and costing nearly a million good-paying jobs.

Big Oil is now effectively exempt from the corporate minimum tax.

Say what you will: Democrats used their power to invest in everyday Americans. Republicans are using theirs to reward their wealthy donors.

Name: Sullivan, Dan
text:
This year, Juneau has experienced a record level of flooding from the annual glacial lake outburst flood (GLOF) down the Mendenhall River‚Äîover 16.5 feet‚Äîtopping last year‚Äôs record of 15.99 feet. In light of these serious challenges and the threat to the lives and property of Alaskans, I have been very focused on getting federal dollars and a workable enduring plan from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to fix this annual challenge in one of our biggest cities. Like I did in the aftermath of last year‚Äôs Juneau flood, I wanted to assess the damage as soon as possible this summer and begin the important work on a durable engineering solution to this problem, which is why I spent all day in Juneau today.
¬†
This morning, I took a helicopter tour of Mendenhall Glacier and the flood zone. I then participated in a very detailed briefing and roundtable discussion with the Unified Command team, including the City and Borough of Juneau, the Central Council of the Tlingit-Haida, the Army Corps of Engineers (USACE), the Coast Guard, the Forest Service, the National Weather Service, and the State of Alaska. I want to commend everyone in the community for their incredible coordination, which no doubt saved lives.
¬†
Regarding next steps, the Corps is a critical partner in both the short-term and in the long-term, enduring solution. That is why, at my request, the recently confirmed Assistant Secretary of the Army for Civil Works, Adam Telle, sent his top leadership for the Pacific Ocean Division‚ÄîBrigadier General Goetz‚Äîto be on the ground immediately to see the situation for himself. Earlier this year, Assistant Secretary Telle committed to me to expedite a solution for Juneau‚Äînot simply accepting another 10 years of studies. The HESCO barriers that were donated by the Corps have overall proven to be a ‚Äúwild success,‚Äù according to the city and the Corps, saving an estimated 1,000 homes from being flooded‚Äîbut they didn‚Äôt work perfectly.¬†
¬†
I truly want to commend USACE Brigadier General Goetz and Command Sergeant Major Zachary Plummer for their outstanding work, and all the time they have spent in the last week on the ground in Juneau, providing reassurance to the citizens of our capital city. I also want to thank Assistant Secretary Telle for already keeping his commitment to me that he would focus his senior team‚Äôs efforts on helping Juneau. 
¬†
I look forward to continue working with all of the stakeholders in Juneau and the Corps to expedite a long-term solution for this community, leveraging the important provisions in President Trump‚Äôs Day One executive order, Unleashing Alaska‚Äôs Extraordinary Resource Potential, which gives the Corps extraordinary powers to work on important Alaska projects, like this one.

Name: Riley, Josh
text:
Last weekend, I visited Israel, including the West Bank and the Gaza border, to see the situation for myself and to speak directly with leaders there, including the head of the UN World Food Program, Palestinian Prime Minister Muhammad Mustafa, Israeli President Isaac Herzog, and senior intelligence officials. The history and politics of the region are complicated, but a few things are clear to me: 

First, there is a severe and undeniable humanitarian crisis in Gaza. More food is now entering Gaza, but it still is not getting to those who need it most. I am demanding that the UN and Israeli government jointly develop an aggressive operation to surge aid to innocent civilians. I pressed President Herzog on this issue, making clear that it is both a moral and a strategic imperative. 

Second, there can be no lasting peace for either Israelis or Palestinians so long as Iran continues to arm and finance terrorist proxies like Hamas, Hezbollah, and the Houthis. Hamas is inflicting unimaginable suffering in the region‚Äìtorturing hostages, depriving innocent Gazans of basic needs, terrorizing Israelis, and unnecessarily prolonging the war that it started on October 7. Hamas needs to release the hostages, surrender its arms, and cede control to leaders who put the Palestinian people ahead of the Iranian regime.  

Third, I appreciate that so many of you feel so passionately about the war.  As a dad to two little kids, it‚Äôs heartbreaking to see images from this war where so many children‚ÄìIsraeli and Palestinian‚Äìare caught in the middle. As Upstate New Yorkers, I hope we can give each other the benefit of the doubt and start from our shared values, knowing that we all want the suffering to end and none of us supports violence against anyone because of how they worship. And we should recognize that we can stand with our allies and their people when they are under attack while still speaking honestly (and critically) to their governments‚Äìjust as we‚Äôd expect them to do with us.

text: I held a job fair on Friday with @GeorgeMasonU. I talked to dozens of employers and people looking for jobs. Here's what I learned about the current state of the economy that the headlines are missing üßµ https://t.co/mbhhNUzIyC

Name: Gonzales, Tony
text: My thoughts are with the Ysleta del Sur Pueblo community as they mourn the loss of Chief Cacique Jose Sierra Sr. His leadership touched many lives‚Äîhe will be missed.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 1. AI is really changing the job market. Companies aren't hiring as many IT and software engineers as they used to, and a lot of people who were told to get STEM degrees are having trouble finding opportunities. Many companies are looking to automate virtually every task and replace employees with new tech.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 2. The Trump and DOGE cuts are hurting Virginia's job market.  But it's not just federal workers, it's people who worked for contractors, people who served those contractors, even people who worked for nonprofits that saw their federal funding get cut. The damage is real and it's hurting everyone.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 3. The job numbers are misleading. They don't count people who have been looking for so long they've all but given up. I met several who fit the category.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 4. There seems to be a premium put on people with hardware experience skills over software. Also, more need for sales and marketing people over back office. And there still seems to be a need for teachers and nurses, though the pay needs to increase to get people to switch fields.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 5. A lot of the federal workers I met actually had to leave on their own or are still at their agency, but making plans to leave soon due to the instability everyday at work. Their work was critical to thousands, sometimes millions, of Americans. These cuts and this brain drain from our fed government will hurt every single American, not just our region.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 6. Employers are overwhelmed with the number of applications. They are getting resumes for entry level jobs from people with 20+ years of experience.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 7. Virginia has an incredible talent pool. People with world class skills and degrees. It's made things really competitive, but also makes us attractive to employers moving here if we put the right talent in place.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 8. It's hard out there for job seekers. People are rightfully frustrated by the lack of opportunities caused by this Administration, and cuts to social safety net only intensify the pressure.

Name: Subramanyam, Suhas
text: 9. In short, I‚Äôll continue fighting these cuts at every juncture and provide resources to help during this difficult time.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Our community has lost a hero‚ÄîCaptain Edward ‚ÄúEd‚Äù Margavich, a life member, Past Chief, and Fire Police Captain of the Third District Volunteer Fire Company, who gave his life in the line of duty. 

For more than sixty years, Ed answered the call with courage and bravery, devoting himself to the protection of others without ever seeking recognition for himself.

His passing is a solemn reminder that our safety rests on the shoulders of men and women who willingly place their neighbors‚Äô lives above their own. That is the very definition of selfless sacrifice‚Äîand it is the spirit that defined Ed‚Äôs life. Known for his wisdom, kindness, and laughter, he will be remembered not only as a leader, but a friend and a constant presence in the fabric of our community.

I ask all to join me in praying for the Margavich family, and for our entire fire service community. A memorial has been placed in front of Station 14 to honor Chief Margavich, and I encourage all to pay their respects and reflect on the legacy of sacrifice and service he leaves behind.

May we never forget him, nor the extraordinary price heroes like Ed pay to keep us safe.

Name: Sullivan, Dan
text:
Pursuing peace is difficult, complicated, and risky. The Trump administration is spending much political capital and taking risks for peace. Since Russia‚Äôs brutal invasion of Ukraine, I have been a strong supporter of Ukraine, including by providing weapons to Ukraine and our NATO allies and hitting Russia with severe sanctions. I want to commend President Trump and his entire team for the relentless time and energy they have put into trying to stop the slaughter in Ukraine launched by the dictator, Putin‚Äîlike they are doing in so many other places in the world: Azerbaijan and Armenia, Cambodia and Thailand, Israel and Iran, Rwanda and the Democratic Republic of the Congo, India and Pakistan, Egypt and Ethiopia, Serbia and Kosovo, and, of course, the Abraham Accords.

I also want to thank President Trump and his team for taking the time to meet with me, my wife, Julie, our entire delegation, and the governor. Friday was a high-pressure day of intense world diplomacy. Despite this, the President and his team‚Äîincluding Secretary of State Rubio, Secretary of Defense Hegseth, Secretary of Commerce Lutnick, Secretary of the Treasury Bessent, Special Envoy Steve Witkoff, White House Chief of Staff Susie Wiles, Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff General Caine, and the Supreme Allied Commander General Grynkewich‚Äîall took the time to meet with me when they touched down in our great state. That was much appreciated.

Finally, to my fellow Alaskans‚Äîso many of whom worked so hard on security for the Alaska Summit and on welcoming people and media from all over the world to our state‚Äîwe have much to be proud of from the Alaska Summit. Thank you and congratulations on showing the world what a great state we live in and just how strategically vital we are for America‚Äôs national and energy security. In particular, I want to thank our remarkable Alaska-based military and law enforcement. You were given an incredibly important mission on a short time frame. And whether it was undertaking security operations for the world leaders at the Alaska Summit, staging our world-class military assets‚Äîlike dozens of 5th generation fighters‚Äîfor all the world to see, or conducting well-timed flyovers to demonstrate to our adversaries the might of the U.S. military, you all conducted this important mission flawlessly. I took a video of this flyover which included our Alaska-based F-35s and a B-2, and was honored to later meet with the B-2 pilots who conducted it.

Thank you all for your hard work and professionalism.

Interesting history lesson for your Sunday evening-

Two thousand years ago, the Silk Road connected China to Rome. It wasn‚Äôt just silk moving along those routes‚Ä¶ it was gunpowder, paper, even the Black Plague. Empires rose and fell depending on who controlled that road. Whoever owned the routes owned the future.

Today, China wants to reimagine the old Silk Road in its ‚ÄúBelt and Road‚Äù Initiative. Today‚Äôs Silk Road is everything from the Panama Canal to the South China Sea to the Suez Canal. Global supply chains are enormously complex. America has led and protected this for the past 80 years, resulting in historic levels of human prosperity and innovation. That‚Äôs why President Trump wants to challenge China‚Äôs quest for dominance and keep us in the driver‚Äôs seat.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1590, John White, governor of the Roanoke colony, returned from a supply trip to England to find the settlement deserted.

Before Jamestown and Plymouth, the English tried to establish a colony at Roanoke Island in present-day North Carolina. When White returned to the colony, the only clue was the word ‚ÄúCROATOAN‚Äù carved into a post, suggesting a move to nearby Croatoan Island, though no settlers were ever found there.

Harsh conditions, including a severe drought between 1587 and 1589, likely played a role in the colony‚Äôs collapse. Some believe the settlers were absorbed into the Croatan tribe, but the mystery remains largely unsolved.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Led by liberal judges, a federal court just undermined one of Congress's most powerful tools to rein in the Administrative State.

The court's decision allows unelected bureaucrats in DC to impose rules that Congress and the President expressly rejected.

Let me explain. üßµ https://t.co/nbbqD2R2YP

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Under the Congressional Review Act, Congress can vote to repeal a regulation issued by an administrative agency.

If the President signs that resolution, then the regulation is repealed and the agency cannot create a "substantially similar" regulation. https://t.co/Frwi3ew6cM

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
That's why I've championed using the CRA to repeal dozens of harmful Biden-era regulations and make sure they don't come back.

For example, Congress and President Trump repealed a series of Biden-Dep't of Energy regs that hurt American energy dominance.
https://t.co/WNK6vpwuhI

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
One of the rules they repealed was from the FCC.

But the unelected bureaucrats at the FCC weren't happy that their regulation had been repealed by your elected representatives and President Trump.

So they waited until Biden took office and then tried again.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
So what happened in this federal appeals court case?

The story starts in 2017 when President Trump and congressional Republicans used the CRA to repeal Obama-era regulations--saving billions of $$ in regulatory costs and millions of paperwork-hours.
https://t.co/ikmAY9B9FX

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Companies affected by the new rule sued, arguing it was illegal for the FCC to re-impose the same rules that Congress and the President repealed using the CRA.

And they were right to do so. The FCC rule blatantly violated the law.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
But two 6th Circuit appeals court judges (an Obama appointee and a Biden appointee) upheld the rule.

They said the new rule wasn't "substantially the same" as the repealed rule because the new rule covered only SOME of the issues that the old rule did.

Let's break that down.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Under the court's logic, the repealed rule and the new rule were not "substantially the same" because the repealed rule covered subjects A+B while the new rule only covered A.

A simple example shows the absurdity of the court's reasoning.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Imagine a mother tells her son: "You are not allowed to stay out past 11pm with your friends."

If the son then stays out past midnight, but does so alone, has the child broken his mother's command?

Common sense and basic logic both say yes. But the court's logic says no.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Here, Congress and the President said to the FCC: "You are not allowed to regulate A+B."

So the Biden FCC‚Äîlike the disobedient child in our example‚Äîtried to be clever and tried to regulate just A.

And the court just let them get away with it. Absurd.
https://t.co/KFMsbqcFeB

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
The 6th Circuit should take this case en banc and reverse this faulty opinion.

And if they don't, then SCOTUS must take the case and restore the full force of the CRA according to the plain meaning of its text. Our separation of powers demands it.

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
The CRA is in need of an overhaul.
https://t.co/sU5iicTrJv

Name: Schmitt, Eric
text:
Congress is paying attention too.

After SCOTUS overturned Chevron, I led a Working Group exploring how Congress can best use that decision to rein in the Administrative State and restore our separation of powers.

For more on the CRA‚Äîcheck out the report.
https://t.co/juDWPtzGLK

The Twin Oaks Pipeline is a clear and present danger to Upper Makefield families ‚Äî and it must be addressed now.

‚úîÔ∏è Full transparency: release all pipeline inspection data
‚úîÔ∏è Real accountability: disclose the findings from PHMSA inspectors
‚úîÔ∏è Safety: shut down the Twin Oaks Pipeline until it is proven safe

From day one, I‚Äôve worked alongside our community task force to fight for answers. Now, we are doubling down on the fight to protect our neighbors and hold Energy Transfer accountable. Name: Moore, Riley M.
text: Given that American voters want elected leaders to prioritize our own interests, and only to deter direct threats with military force when necessary, and when no other actors can credibly do so independent of US action, policymakers need to prioritize two considerations.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text: First, the point of the US military is not simply to fight and win wars, but also to deter conflict before it happens. This requires maintaining American technical superiority on a domain-by-domain basis. In some arenas, exquisite platforms like stealth bombers, will be critical to deterrence. In others, a massive advantage in raw materials will be the deterrent.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text: To build any of these at scale, we need to have a much larger and more diversified industrial base. The saying goes, ‚ÄúIf you want peace, prepare for war.‚Äù This does not just mean building more ships. It means building national capacity across the industrial sector so that in the event of a major war, the United States can quickly retool civilian manufacturing to drastically ramp up military production.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text: Our movement and this administration are at a crossroads. None of Iran‚Äôs proxies, partners, or allies have come to Tehran‚Äôs immediate aid. As a result, the opportunity for peace may have presented itself. With Iran isolated, there is a very small window to provide greater stability in the region. This is not to say America can trust the Iranians‚Äîbut with negotiations, confidence-building measures, and a serious verification regime in place, we can make significant progress. Crucially, that progress will be backed by a credible threat of massive and overwhelming force.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text: Second, policymakers need to exercise humility about where they commit the United States to act. There are countries that for a litany of reasons‚Äîhistorical,      cultural, religious, or otherwise‚Äî do not want or cannot become Western-style democracies, at least not on a timeline or at a cost that the American people will bear.

‚úÖ Secure federal cleanup funding for local communities
‚úÖ Press the Pentagon to accelerate remediation at defense sites
‚úÖ Introduce bipartisan legislation codifying EPA‚Äôs first-ever PFAS drinking water standards

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On this day in history in 1953, the Iranian military, with the support of the CIA, orchestrated a coup to overthrow Premier Mohammad Mosaddeq to reinstate the Shah of Iran. 

The CIA, collaborating with British intelligence, made a plan to remove Mosaddeq, despite his efforts to rally public support. The coup succeeded, and the Shah was restored to power, granting U.S. companies significant oil concessions in return for their support. Mosaddeq was imprisoned and died under house arrest in 1967.

The Shah became a key Cold War ally for the U.S., receiving substantial aid until anti-Shah protests led to his overthrow in 1979. The subsequent hostage crisis at the U.S. embassy marked the end of a significant American influence in Iran.

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Brandywine Valley Active Aging has operated in Coatesville and Downingtown dating back to the 1970's and provides emergency rental assistance, food services, and one-on-one support to seniors.

I have spoken a lot recently about the impact that President Trump's Big Ugly Bill will have on our community. Cuts to SNAP assistance, Medicare and Medicaid, community health programs and more are not just theoretical, they have very real consequences.

Approximately 445,000 seniors and people with disabilities in PA rely on Medicaid to help afford their Medicare expenses, including premiums and out-of-pocket costs.

Medicaid pays for care for 3 in 5 PA nursing home residents and it is estimated that PA will lose $53 billion in federal Medicaid funding over the next 10 years. The Governor's office has estimated 310,000 Pennsylvanians will lose their Medicaid coverage entirely.

While Republicans are celebrating the passage of this bill, my colleagues and I are in our communities hearing directly from those impacted. Keep calling, keep writing, keep pushing lawmakers to stand up for seniors. It makes a difference.

Name: Arrington, Jodey C.
text:
Just weeks after rescinding Biden‚Äôs radical Green New Deal proposal to expand the Muleshoe Wildlife Refuge by over 10,000%, we‚Äôre back in Bailey County discussing the importance of standing up for Rural America against federal overreach. ¬†
¬†
I vehemently opposed this federal land grab for several reasons:

First, I believe in private property rights. The federal government should not take over vast swaths of land in the name of radical environmental initiatives like Biden‚Äôs 30x30 Plan and the Green New Deal.  

Second, the claim that the expansion was necessary to protect endangered species is simply not true, as the populations of the animals listed under this plan are thriving.

Third, the federal government has failed to manage the land it already controls, as the maintenance backlog for the National Wildlife Refuge System is over $2.6 billion. If the government can‚Äôt manage the land it already owns, why in the world would we expect that it can handle more?

Fourth, the slashing of the local tax base would decimate schools, public safety, and important services in West Texas, as the federal government does not adequately reimburse communities for land purchases.

Fifth, this would enable more federal overreach similar to the Biden Administration‚Äôs weaponization of federal agencies against farmers, independent energy producers, and the State of Texas‚Äôs efforts to secure the border.

And, finally, at a time when our nation‚Äôs debt has surpassed WWII levels, the federal government has no business spending your tax dollars to expand federal land.
